Introduction¶

In 2001, Nintendo released Super Smash Bros. Melee for their new GameCube console. Attempting to follow up the success of the original Super Smash Bros. (released on Nintendo 64), Melee is a crossover platform figher featuring 26 characters from Nintendo's other franchises. Melee went on to sell over 7 million copies as the GameCube's best performing game and a competitive scene of players aiming to be the worlds best immediately emerged. A 2013 documentary called The Smash Brothers would catapult Melee's scene into the spotlight and establish it as one of esports' biggest games. The community has only grown since then and 2022 has been one of competitive Melee's biggest years.

Competitive Melee is played in a tournament setting where many players show up to a venue for a 1-3 day event and compete for the top spot. Tournaments are run as double-elimination brackets (when you lose twice you're out) where players compete in best-of-3 or best-of-5 sets. A fundamentally grassroots community, most local Melee scenes are defined by one or two weekly local tournaments. Regional tournaments and national tournaments happen every few weeks in most areas but the most important tournaments are known as majors and supermajors: massive tournaments with thousands of dollars in prizes and the opportunity to compete against the world's best. Major results are critical to joining the most important list in Melee: SSBMRank. Published at the end of each year since 2013 (excepting 2020-1 due to COVID-19), SSBMRank asks a panel of Melee's most influential names (commentators, top level players, tournament organizers, and scene figureheads) to rank the best players and compiles the results into a top 100 list published at the end of the year.

This page was written for an undergraduate Data Science assignment to create a tutorial "that walks the reader through the Data Science pipeline". I will be working with the Smash Player Database, a collection of nearly all Smash tournament data since ~2015. Panel rankings such as SSBMRank give good insight into the consensus of the scene's leaders - but groups of people have bias and algorithmic ranking systems can come with their own insight. In this tutorial I intend to a) consider a few algorithmic ranking systems, b) compare these ranking systems to each other and themselves, and c) use the best ranking systems to find some interesting stories in Melee. At the time of writing, Ludwig's Scuffed World Tour is the only significant tournament pending for the year and SSBMRank 2022 should be released soon after. Let's see if we can say anything about what those results might look like!

A few quick notes before I dive in to the dataset:

  • A highly influential mod known as Slippi released an option to play Melee online with rollback netcode (a necessity in the fast paced Fighting Game genre) in 2020 and some tournaments are now online - in keeping with Fighting Game tradition, however, I will only be analyzing offline sets.

  • If you're reading this only because you care about Melee, skip to Hypothesis Testing and Data Visualization at the bottom.

  • If you're reading this because you care about Data Science (or because you're grading this assignment), you may be vaguely aware of Melee because of recurring drama stemming from continuing Intellectual Property rights disputes between the grassroots scene and Nintendo. I won't be going into this at all in this report - I am much better at data analysis than legal anaylsis ;). Just know that competitive Melee exists in spite of, rather than because of, Nintendo.

  • This report will be structured after a somewhat personal reinterpretation of the Data Analysis pipeline:

    1. Data Collection - get everything stored on memory (in rubric as: "Data collection/curation + parsing (if necessary)" and "Data management/representation")
    2. Exploratory Analysis - try some techniques and ask a bunch of questions (in rubric as: "Exploratory Data Analysis")
    3. Hypothesis Testing and Data Visualization - dive deeper into the questions that had interesting answers (in rubric as "Hypothesis testing" and "communication of insights attained")

Data Collection¶

As mentioned above, I will be working with the Smash Player Database. This is actually composed of separate databases for each Smash game (at the time of writing only Melee and Ultimate have active scenes) but I will only be looking at Melee data. Before anything else, let's figure out exactly what's contained within this downloaded database:

In this phase of the analysis I will load all the data I'm interested in working with onto memory - both to centralize database calls and reduce potential work if something breaks and to get a sense of all the data available to me. I'll do no analysis of the data beyond reading and commenting on data tables.

External libraries I will use for this section include pandas for its collection data types (most notably DataFrame for tables and Series for 1d data) and tqdm to show progress indicators.

This shows separate tables for player data, sets, tournaments, and rankings that I will assemble into separate pd.DataFrame objects - these will form the basis for all later analysis. Ranking seasons is an association table that will be summarilly ignored.

I'll start by querying the players table. Character usage is given as a json-formatted characters attribute in the original table - I will parse the json and replace the attribute with much more meaningful columns for primary character, secondary character, and number of sets with primary, secondary, and other characters. I'll also create some helper functions to help swap between the unique player_id column and the human readable tag column to help display results later.

In [ ]:
import json
import numpy as np
from collections import Counter

players_query = "SELECT player_id, tag, region, state, country, characters FROM players;" # query to get all data
raw_players_df = pd.read_sql(players_query, conn) # place the query


# character usage is stored as a json - lets get primary character + secondary character data 
def parse_char_dict(chars_str): 
    char_dict = Counter(json.loads(chars_str))
    
    if char_dict: # if any character usage is stored at all, get primary
        primary_char, primary_char_uses = char_dict.most_common(1)[0]
        primary_char = primary_char.replace("melee/", "") # we know theyre melee characters already lol
    else:
        primary_char, primary_char_uses = np.NaN, 0


    if len(char_dict.most_common(2)) > 1: # if multiple characters are stored, get secondary
        secondary_char, secondary_char_uses = char_dict.most_common(2)[1]
        secondary_char = secondary_char.replace("melee/", "") # we know theyre melee characters already lol

    else:
        secondary_char, secondary_char_uses = np.NaN, 0

    other_uses = sum(char_dict.values()) - (primary_char_uses + secondary_char_uses)

    return primary_char, primary_char_uses, secondary_char, secondary_char_uses, other_uses


primary_char, primary_char_uses, secondary_char, secondary_char_uses, other_uses = \
    zip(*raw_players_df["characters"].apply(parse_char_dict)) # extract all of these into their own series


# we've got all we need - let's make the players dataframe!
players_df = pd.DataFrame()
players_df["player_id"] = raw_players_df["player_id"].apply(str)
players_df["tag"] = raw_players_df["tag"]
players_df["region"] = raw_players_df["region"]
players_df["state"] = raw_players_df["state"]
players_df["country"] = raw_players_df["country"]
players_df["primary_char"] = primary_char
players_df["primary_char_games"] = primary_char_uses
players_df["secondary_char"] = secondary_char
players_df["secondary_char_games"] = secondary_char_uses
players_df["other_char_games"] = other_uses

# takes an iterable of player_ids, returns generator of respective tags
def get_tags(id_iter):
    for id in id_iter:
        search = players_df[players_df["player_id"] == str(id)]
        yield search.iloc[0]["tag"] if not search.empty else id

# takes an iterable of tags, returns generator of BEST-GUESS ids (remember that multiple players can use the same tag)
def get_ids(tag_iter):
    for tag in tag_iter:
        search = players_df[players_df["tag"] == tag]
        yield search.iloc[0]["player_id"] if not search.empty else tag

Next I'll query the tournament results table. As mentioned above, I will only consider offline events. Placements for each tournament are stored in a single json attribute that I will parse and insert into the DataFrame as separate columns for each placing.

Remember that these are double elimination tournaments - Player X appearing above Player Y on a row of this table means "X placed at least as well as Y" and NOT that "X placed better than Y". I'll store the list of places for later too - it will help identify tied tournament placements later.

In [ ]:
tourney_query = "SELECT key, cleaned_name, season, entrants, placings FROM tournament_info WHERE online==0;" # query to get all data

raw_tourney_df = pd.read_sql(tourney_query, conn) # place the query

# we'll use this to remember how much each place is worth later
max_places = []

# placings are stored as list of lists [[first_id, 1], [second_id, 2]] etc
# lets extract into separate columns for each placement that we care about!
# remember that these are double elimination tournaments and placement is
# largely ignored in rankings - so all we care about is top 8 placements
def parse_placings(placings_str):
    global max_places

    try:
        placings_list = json.loads(placings_str)
        placings_list = filter(lambda x: type(x[1]) == int, placings_list) # filter duplicate str placements
        placings_list = sorted(placings_list, key=lambda x: x[1] if x[1] > 0 else 10**10) # sort

        ids, places = zip(*placings_list)
        ids = pd.Series(ids).drop_duplicates().to_list()

        if len(places) > len(max_places):
            max_places = places

        return pd.DataFrame([ids])

    except AssertionError:

        return pd.DataFrame([np.NaN])

    except ValueError:

        return pd.DataFrame([np.NaN])


# we've got all we need, let's make the tourney dataframe
tourney_df = pd.concat(raw_tourney_df["placings"].apply(parse_placings).to_list()).reset_index()
tourney_df["key"] = raw_tourney_df["key"]
tourney_df["cleaned_name"] = raw_tourney_df["cleaned_name"]
tourney_df["season"] = raw_tourney_df["season"]
tourney_df["entrants"] = raw_tourney_df["entrants"]

del(tourney_df["index"])

tourney_df = tourney_df[tourney_df["entrants"] > 0] # filter empty tourneys

sets_query = """
SELECT sets.key, sets.tournament_key, sets.winner_id, sets.p1_id, sets.p2_id, sets.p1_score, sets.p2_score, tournament_info.season
FROM sets INNER JOIN tournament_info
    ON sets.tournament_key == tournament_info.key
    WHERE tournament_info.online == 0
""" # query to get all sets from offline tournaments only

sets_df = pd.read_sql(sets_query, conn) # place the query

Exploratory Analysis¶

Now that we have all of our relevant data stored on memory lets try out some ranking algorithms and ask questions about what they say! In this phase of the analysis I will be implementing and testing a number of algorithms to rank players for each season. I'll ask a lot of questions but answer them in pretty shallow ways, marking down interesting results to look more closely at in the next phase of analysis.

Before we start I'm making a helper function to narrow down the list of contenders and help reduce computational complexity. I'll create a function to pull all players who placed above a given place at a tournament with a given number of entrants - notably, this is how eligibility for SSBMRank was decided back when the methodology was open.

In [ ]:
def top_k_more_than_n_entrants(k, n, season=22, or_win=False):
    tourneys = tourney_df[tourney_df["season"] == season]
    tourneys = tourneys[tourneys["entrants"] >= n]

    places = [tourneys[i] for i in range(k)]
    by_placement = pd.concat(places)
    
    if or_win:
        winners = tourney_df[tourney_df["season"] == season][0]
        return pd.concat([winners, by_placement]).drop_duplicates().dropna().to_list()
    else:
        return by_placement.drop_duplicates().dropna().to_list()

Winrate¶

The most intuitive way to rank players is to see how "winning" they are - what percentage of their games do they win? Breaking our data down into seasons, let's look at the winningest players from each season.

In [ ]:
def get_winrate(player_id, season=22):
    seasonal_df = sets_df[sets_df["season"] == season]

    p1_results = seasonal_df[seasonal_df["p1_id"] == player_id]["p1_win"]
    p2_results = ~seasonal_df[seasonal_df["p2_id"] == player_id]["p1_win"]
    wins = p1_results.sum() + p2_results.sum()
    played = p1_results.shape[0] + p2_results.shape[0]

    return wins / played

candidate_ids = top_k_more_than_n_entrants(64, 300, season=19)
candidates = players_df[players_df["player_id"].isin(candidate_ids)].copy()
candidates["winrate"] = candidates["player_id"].progress_apply(get_winrate)
candidates.sort_values(by="winrate", ascending=False).head(10)

These don't look like a list of top players at all(besides a Hungrybox copycat who won a single tournament)! What looks to be happening is that players who often attend and win their local tournaments end up with a very high winrate - this does make sense, and is why winrate is a pretty limited metric for ranking. Let's test how well correlated this chart is with SSBMRank for each season.

I will use an external library named scipy for this and future p-value calculations.

In [ ]:
import scipy.stats as stats

for season, season_ranks in rankings_df.groupby("season"):
    candidate_ids = season_ranks[0:100].iloc[0]
    candidates = players_df[players_df["player_id"].isin(candidate_ids)].copy()

    winrate = candidates["player_id"].apply(get_winrate, season=int(season)-2000).dropna()
    # data is incomplete for 2015, drop unknown winrate

    rho, p_val = stats.spearmanr(range(len(winrate)), winrate)
    print(str(season) + ": rho of", rho, "(p=" + str(p_val) + ")")

2015: rho of 0.231247678905747 (p=0.02339666895845368)
2016: rho of -0.10658879192183571 (p=0.29119790003589435)
2017: rho of -0.2899304783678737 (p=0.0034337833419486705)
2018: rho of -0.1534970908266835 (p=0.12732803658716071)
2019: rho of -0.174776579320655 (p=0.08199864872006755)

To explain the hypothesis test here, we have a null hypothesis of these data having different underlying rank distributions and calculate a spearman's rho (a measure of rank correlation) between -1 and 1. We should expect a very strong negative correlation here - higher winrate should lead to lower rank! This is not borne out, with all of the yearly Spearman's rho values being quite close to zero. In addition, 2 out of 5 years have p-values that make rejecting the null hypothesis very difficult. Before we move on let's try and understand what an excellent winrate does look like by analyzing winrates for players on the official rankings.

I use an external library called matplotlib and a wrapper library around it called seaborn to help with this and future figure generating.

In [ ]:
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

winrate_rankings = {}
for i in range(5):
    top_100 = rankings_df.iloc[i]
    for rank, id in enumerate(top_100):
        winrate_rankings[(i*100) + rank] = [rank, get_winrate(id, season=15+i), 15+i]

winrate_df = pd.DataFrame.from_dict(winrate_rankings, orient="index", columns=["rank", "winrate", "season"])
sns.lineplot(data=winrate_df, x="rank", y="winrate", hue="season");

This figure helps us understand further why simple winrate is a poor ranking metric - we can see that many of the worlds best players have historically had pretty bad and even negative winrates! Additionally, winrate variance of the top 100 is very high. Instead, we'll need to use something a little bit more sophisticated!

Glicko-2¶

Some wins are clearly more impressive than others - what if we could modify winrate to reward impressive wins more and unimpressive wins less? This is the basis for Glicko-2, a rating system widely used in 2 player games such as chess. In keeping with the imprecision of chess terminology, I will also be referring to this as ELO (the system that Glicko-2 replaced). I'll also refer to it as MMR (MatchMaking Rating) - this is also not quite the same, but all are used to refer to systems that algorithmically predict how likely a certain player is to beat another one (and all three are rarely used precisely). Let's see what happens if we apply it to Melee.

Instead of rolling my own Glicko-2 implementation, I will use one available online.

In [ ]:
import glicko2

def update_ranks(set, season_players):
    p1_id, p2_id, p1_win = set["p1_id"], set["p2_id"], set["p1_win"]
    
    if p1_id not in season_players:
        season_players[p1_id] = glicko2.Player()
    if p2_id not in season_players:
        season_players[p2_id] = glicko2.Player()

    p1, p2 = season_players[p1_id], season_players[p2_id]

    p1.update_player([p2.rating], [p2.rd], [p1_win])
    p2.update_player([p1.rating], [p1.rd], [not p1_win])
    

season_elo_dfs = {}
elo_ranks = {}
for season, season_sets in sets_df.groupby("season"):
    if season:
        season_players = {}

        season_sets.apply(update_ranks, season_players=season_players, axis=1)
        mmr = pd.Series(season_players).apply(lambda player: player.rating)

        season_df = players_df[players_df["player_id"].isin(season_players)].copy().set_index("player_id")
        season_df["mmr"] = mmr

        mmr_top_100 = season_df.sort_values("mmr", ascending=False).head(100).index.to_list()
        elo_ranks[season] = mmr_top_100

        season_elo_dfs[season] = season_df
        season_elo_dfs[season]["season"] = season

        
elo_ranks = pd.DataFrame.from_dict(elo_ranks, orient="index")
elo_ranks.apply(lambda row: [*get_tags(row)])

Glicko-2 vs SSBMRank¶

This looks way more like a top ranking! Let's start off by comparing this ranking to SSBMRank and see how well it matches.

Great! This shows the spearman's rho that we expected - quite close to -1, and with p values small enough that we can reasonably reject the null hypothesis of ELO having a different underlying rank distribution than SSBMRank. Let's take a look closer at ELO distribution.

Distribution of Glicko-2¶

The first thing to look at to understand the distribution of Glicko-2 scores is... well... simply the distribution of Glicko-2 scores! I'll make a density plot of all scores to see if anything pops out.

In [ ]:

Glicko-2 Trained on Tournament Results¶

The Glicko-2 results looked quite promising - but don't include any sort of reward for winning or placing well at tournaments! This is often the most important factor publically discussed by SSBMRank panelists so let's try making a system to rate players by tournament placing. Since Glicko-2 has already proven itself, I'll try using it again - this time counting a win as "outplacing someone in a tournament" and a loss as... not... doing that?

In [ ]:
def update_ranks_tourney(tourney, season_players):
    players = pd.Series(tourney[0:2340]).dropna().to_list()
    rankings = max_places[:len(players)]

    for player in players:
        if player not in season_players:
            season_players[player] = glicko2.Player(vol=.0001)

    ratings = [season_players[player].rating for player in players]
    rds = [season_players[player].rd for player in players]
    
    for i, player in enumerate(players):
        player_ratings = ratings[:i] + (ratings[i+1:] if i+1 < len(players) else [])
        player_rds = rds[:i] + (rds[i+1:] if i+1 < len(rds) else [])

        player_rank = rankings[i]
        player_results = [int(player_rank <= rank) for rank in rankings]
        del player_results[i]

        season_players[player].update_player(player_ratings, player_rds, player_results) 

season_tourney_elo_dfs = {}
tourney_elo_ranks = {}

        mmr = pd.Series(season_players).apply(lambda player: player.rating)

        season_df = players_df[players_df["player_id"].isin(season_players)].copy().set_index("player_id")

Points Gained by Tourney Placements¶

Glicko-2 seems imperfect for rewarding tournament placements so let's try a more normal system. One very common system for rewarding tournament systems is to assign each tournament a total point value based on size and then give players points based on their placements. To avoid rewarding players for showing up and winning the same small tournament over and over, many such systems also cap the number of tournaments a player can be rewarded for (these are often referred to as markers). I'll assign each tournament a point value based on the number of entrants - first let's look at the distribution!

This "normal" system is heavily inspired by the points system used in the American Parliamentary Debate Association standings for Player of the Year / Team of the Year but it's also notably similar to a ranking system used in Melee's sequel's sequel's sequel (Smash Ultimate) known as OrionRank. (I know the wiki reports a different methodology for OrionRank - it's been changed, the wiki is just out of data :P).

In [ ]:
sns.histplot(tourney_df, x="entrants", log_scale=True);

Looking at this chart (and this one) we can make three categories

  • Local (< 100 entrants): 5pts for win
  • Regional (100 - 250 entrants): 10pts for win, 5pt for top 8
  • Major (> 250 entrants): 20pts for win, 10pt for top 8

We'll also only count a players 5 best placings, making 100 a perfect score.

Let's look at tournaments from this year to match up:

In [ ]:
def grade_size(tourney):
    if tourney["entrants"] > 250:
        return "major"
    elif tourney["entrants"] > 100:
        return "regional"
    else:
        return "local"

tourney_df["grade"] = tourney_df.apply(grade_size, axis=1)
tourney_df[(tourney_df["season"] == 22)]["grade"].value_counts()
Out[ ]:
local       7402
regional      38
major         13
Name: grade, dtype: int64

This looks about right! This doesn't take into account invitationals, as those tend to have smaller entrants - I'm okay with this though, as rankings in a grassroots community should probably be based on open tournaments anyway.

Now let's actually generate tournament points for everyone who made at least top 8 at a regional or won a local:

In [ ]:
def get_tourney_points(player_id, season=22):
    seasonal_df = tourney_df[tourney_df["season"] == season]
    majors = seasonal_df[seasonal_df["grade"] == "major"]
    regionals = seasonal_df[seasonal_df["grade"] == "regional"]
    locals = seasonal_df[seasonal_df["grade"] == "locals"]

    major_wins = sum(majors[0] == player_id)
    major_podia = sum([sum(majors[i] == player_id) for i in range(1, 8)])

    regional_wins = sum(regionals[0] == player_id)
    regional_podia = sum([sum(regionals[i] == player_id) for i in range(1, 8)])

    local_wins = sum(locals[0] == player_id)

    markers = [20 for _i in range(major_wins)] + [10 for _i in range(major_podia)] + \
              [10 for _i in range(regional_wins)] + [5 for _i in range(regional_podia)] + \
              [5 for _i in range(local_wins)]

    if len(markers) <= 5:
        return sum(markers)
    else:
        return sum(markers[:5])

season_tourney_point_dfs = {}
for season in tqdm(range(15, 20)):
    candidate_ids = top_k_more_than_n_entrants(8, 100, season=season, or_win=True)
    season_tourney_points_df = players_df[players_df["player_id"].isin(candidate_ids)].copy()
    
    season_tourney_points_df["tourney_points"] = \
        season_tourney_points_df["player_id"].apply(get_tourney_points, season=season)

    season_tourney_point_dfs[season] = season_tourney_points_df.set_index("player_id")
    season_tourney_point_dfs[season]["season"] = season

tourney_point_df = pd.concat([season_tourney_point_dfs[season].reset_index() for season in range(15, 20)])
tourney_point_df.sort_values("tourney_points", ascending=False).head()

Hypothesis Testing and Data Visualization¶

For this phase of the analysis, I will answer a number of practical questions with some degree of certainty. Unlike the last phase, which focused on coming up with questions, this phase will give meaningful and understandable answers to a short list of interesting quesions:

  • In our last step, we marked two things down as being worth revisiting later:
    1. Is ELO of top players dropping?
    2. I noticed Fox performs better in Tourney Points ranking than SSBMRank - Can I explain what is happening?

  • So far, we've only been analyzing games from 2015-2019 as those are the games with associated SSBMRanks. Now that we've picked our two favorite ranking systems(Glicko-2 and Tourney Points), let's also take a look at this years competition!

    1. What will character composition of this year's Top 100 look like?
    2. Word on the street has it that this year is closer than usual - is this true?

Is Top Player Skill Dropping?¶

As mentioned above, the Glicko-2 ratings for top players appear to have dropped off in recent years. Let's begin by making a new plot to look at ELO distribution of top 100 players for each season.

In [ ]:

ax.set_ylabel("Glicko-2 Rating");

This is clearer than the last figure and it really does look like top 100 player ELOs are worse in 2019 than they were in 2018. Before we move on, let's confirm this visual intuition with a hypothesis test. We'll compare the 2018 SSBMRank ELOs to the 2019 SSBMRank ELOS with a null hypothesis that they share a population mean (equivalently, that top100 players were exactly as good in 2018 as 2019).

In [ ]:
season_18_top_100 = season_top_100s.loc[2018]["mmr"]
season_19_top_100 = season_top_100s.loc[2019]["mmr"]

t_stat, p_val = stats.ttest_ind(season_18_top_100, season_19_top_100)

print("These distributions have a t-stat of", t_stat, "(p="+str(p_val)+")")

These distributions have a t-stat of 2.6261855855899916 (p=0.009309834509149725)

This p-value is below .01 - low enough for me to confidently reject the null hypothesis and say that 2019s top players really did have a lower ELO than 2018s top players. Importantly, this does NOT mean that top player skill fell - Glicko-2 only makes sense within a system of players, so this says something more along the lines of "the gap between top players and average ones fell between 2018 and 2019". I would be most likely to blame this on an increase in average player skill as one of Melee's biggest booms came to an end and players had been playing the game for a longer time.

Why Do Foxes Get More Tournament Points?¶

(Note: If you've never played Melee, it's worth noting that Fox is a unique character as the uncontested best in the game since the 8th official tier list released in 2006. Fox is also Melee's most iconic character, with his special move "reflector" - known by fans as "shine" - generating a blue hexagon that is the primary symbol of Melee. Also, if you've never played Melee, now's a great time to start!)

Another oddity I noticed earlier was that Foxes seem to do better in Tournament Point rankings than SSBMRank - let's generate a plot confirming that suspicion.

In [ ]:
def is_fox_main(player_id):
    char = players_df[players_df["player_id"] == player_id].iloc[0]["primary_char"]

    return char == "fox"


for season, season_ranks in rankings_df.groupby("season"):
    candidate_ids = season_ranks[0:100].iloc[0]
    season_rankings = season_tourney_point_dfs[int(season)-2000]["tourney_points"]

    all_points = [ season_rankings[id] if id in season_rankings else 0 for id in candidate_ids] 
    all_ranks = pd.Series(all_points).rank(ascending=False)
    all_indices = pd.Series(range(1, 101))

    fox_mains = [is_fox_main(player) for player in candidate_ids]

    fox_ranks = all_ranks[fox_mains]
    fox_indices = all_indices[fox_mains]

    t_stat, p_val = stats.ttest_ind(fox_ranks, fox_indices)
    print("These distributions have a t-stat of", t_stat, "(p="+str(p_val)+")")

These distributions have a t-stat of 0.6573737414780649 (p=0.513732991242952)

These distributions have a t-stat of -0.047220807070965744 (p=0.9625114538157872)
These distributions have a t-stat of -0.1637058691889304 (p=0.8705973225491817)

Whelp, I guess I misread the original figure :P. These p-values are incredibly high - it would be quite silly to reject the null hypothesis, so it seems like Fox mains are ranked more or less the same whether by SSBMRank or Tourney Points ranking.

Is This Year Actually More Competitive?¶

The last major question I want to answer is whether this year was actually more competitive at the very top than past years. Panelists are known to rarely value head-to-head results as much as tournament placings so we'll calculate Tourney Point differences between top five players for each past year. Once we have that it should be easy to compare it against this year's standings and see if the difference in competition is actually visible.

In [ ]:
top_5_tp_vals = []

for season in range(15, 20):
    tp_top_5 = tourney_point_df[tourney_point_df["season"] == season].sort_values("tourney_points", ascending=False).head(5)

    top_5_tp_vals.append(tp_top_5["tourney_points"].to_list())
    print(2000+season, np.var(tp_top_5["tourney_points"]))

print(2022, np.var(ytd_tourney_points_df.sort_values("tourney_points", ascending=False).head()["tourney_points"]))

2015 184.0
2016 136.0
2017 184.0
2018 216.0
2019 344.0
2022 56.0

Woah - that's a massive difference! The average variance in tourney points lies somewhere around 200, but this year is 56. Samples of dimension 5 are unlikely to provide enough n for a meaningful hypothesis test, but let's try it anyway! We'll test two null hypotheses - the first being that 2015-2019 rankings have the same underlying variance, and the second being that 2015-2019 and 2022 have the same underlying variance.

In [ ]:
_stat, p = stats.levene(*top_5_tp_vals)

print("The probability of a levene stat at least as strong as this for 2015-2019 stats with the same variance is:", p)

_stat, p = stats.levene(*top_5_tp_vals, ytd_tourney_points_df.sort_values("tourney_points", ascending=False).head()["tourney_points"].to_list())
print("The probability of a levene stat at least as strong as this for 2015-2019 and 2022 stats with the same variance is:", p)

The probability of a levene stat at least as strong as this for 2015-2019 stats with the same variance is: 0.9970132556861661
The probability of a levene stat at least as strong as this for 2015-2019 and 2022 stats with the same variance is: 0.969135737870656

As expected, we don't have enough evidence to solidly reject the null hypothesis and suggest that anything real has changed here - a SSBMRank this close, while novel, falls within the bounds we expect to occasionally see due to random chance. Regardless of that fact, this year was still much closer than all previous years - just not enough to suggest that the underlying variability of ranking has changed.

Conclusion¶

2022 marked the return of massive offline Melee tournaments and a renewed excitement surrounding the years SSBMRank. I've introduced two algorithmic alternatives to SSBMRank that also attempt to rank players based on the year's performance, one Glicko-2 based system that trains on set results and one Marker based system that trains on tournament results. While both of these metrics rank players based on the same underlying characteristics as SSBMRank (at least, there is statistically significant evidence of highly correlated ranks), neither one is particularly effective at predicting the SSBMRank wholesale. Despite this, these rankings delivered a few major insights:

  • peak ELO, or how likely a top player is to beat an average player, has fallen since Melee's peak
  • this year's competition at the top really is much closer than any year past - although there's not enough to reject the possibility that it's because of random chance rather than the top players being closer than before

In addition, I've provided a couple of interesting tables / figures to help understand what this years SSBMRank might look like:

  • the top 100 players of the year by Glicko-2 rating (potential ranked players)
  • the 80 players who have placed well enough at tournaments to earn a Tournament Points rating for this year (likely ranked players)
  • main character composition of these potential ranked players + character compositions of past SSBMRanks to compare
